[1
Date: 10 Jul 2000 11:16:13 -0000
From: Simon Reid <sreid@central.murdoch.edu.au>

There appears to be some confusion over the exact etiology of this outbreak
of disease in Bengal Tigers. If trypanosomes have been observed in the
blood of clinically affected tigers (and I assume they have) then the
species is _Trypanosoma evansi_ which is endemic in India and transmitted
by tabanid biting flies. Oral transmission of _T. evansi_ also occurs and
is thought to be the main route of infection for carnivores (Hoare, 1972).
As I see it there are 2 possible explanations for this outbreak. First, the
tigers were infected by tabanids feeding on ruminants housed within 50
meters or so, that were infected with _T. evansi_. Or secondly, and more
likely, the first tiger to show clinical signs (and possibly its cell
mates) was infected by ingestion of freshly killed meat from a ruminant
infected with _T. evansi_.
Regardless of the source of infection treatment of ALL remaining animals
with a curative trypanocidal drug should be effective at halting this
outbreak. Cymelarsan is effective at a dose rate between 0.75 - 1 mg/kg and
should be safe to use in tigers (it is safely used to treat heartworm in
dogs and _T. evansi_ infection in camels). I am not sure how toxic other
drugs such as Diminazine aceturate or Quinapyramine sulphate are in carnivores.
If there is still some doubt about the final diagnosis it could be achieved
post mortem. Histological changes are reasonably characteristic. The
picture seen is of a mononuclear cell infiltration in the connective tissue
of most organs, in particular, heart, lung, kidney, stomach and large
intestine. Immunohistochemistry can be used to confirm that _T. evansi_ is
present in the tissues.
Hoare CA (1972) The Trypanosomes of mammals. A zoological monograph.
Blackwell Scientific Publications, Oxford, UK.
--
Dr Simon Reid BVMS, PhD, MACVSc. (Epidemiology)
Western Australian Biotechnology Research Institute
Division of Veterinary and Biomedical Sciences
Murdoch University
Western Australia, 6150
<sreid@central.murdoch.edu.au>
[Dr. Reid, we appreciate you sharing your insight with us. - Mod.TG
