Date: 8 Jul 2000
From: Héctor Paz Atencio <glodys45@hotmail.com>
Source: The Times of India <http://www.timesofindia.com/>
<http://www.timesofindia.com/today/08hlth1.htm> 8 Jul 2000 [edited

BHUBANESWAR: One more Royal Bengal tiger, a white male, died at Nandankanan
zoo on Friday. The number of tigers having died since Tuesday evening has
risen to 12. The zoo is now left with 44 tigers - 19 white and 25 normal.
An expert team led by P. R. Sinha, member-secretary, Central Zoo Authority,
arrived earlier in the day. The team comprises a wildlife expert from
Hyderabad, 2 veterinarians from Chennai and the Veterinary Council of India
and the assistant director of the Bangalore zoo.
Official sources said Union minister Maneka Gandhi had spoken to some
international tiger experts in the US and the UK, who are likely to reach
here in a few days. The government had sought the help of experts of the
Wildlife Institute at Dehra Dun and the Indian Veterinary Research
Institute (IVRI) at Izatnagar near Bareilly.
The gravity of the situation can be gauged by zoo experts and environmental
activists from all over the world having expressed concern over the
developments at Nandankanan and offering assistance for the safety of the
surviving tigers, according to Biswajit Mohanty of the Wildlife Society of
Orissa. The tiger population in the wild in Orissa has declined from 226 in
1993 to 194 by May 2000, largely due to a sharp loss in their habitant and
unchecked poaching. The world population of white tigers is not more than
200. With this background, the decision of the Nandankanan zoo authorities
to administer a "toxic" drug like Bernyl to the tigers without diagnosing
whether or not they were actually suffering from "tripanosomiasis"
[trypanosomiasis has sparked widespread resentment.
However, the zoo authorities defended their decision stating Bernyl was the
"right choice". "It is true the tigers were not medically examined to
identify the disease before being given the drug. But after the death of
Debasis on June 23, we apprehended the 17 other tigers in the nearby
enclosures that might have contracted tripanosomiasis [trypanosomiasis and
hence decided to give them Bernyl," chief conservator of forests S.K.
Patnaik said.
He asserted Bernyl was not "toxic" in nature. It has been used in the past
without having any adverse effect on the animals. Bernyl was given as a
preventive measure. The tigers died due to the disease, not an overdose of
the medicine.
Patnaik denied the deaths had anything to do with the proliferation of
tigers in captivity through inbreeding. The genetic chart of each tiger in
Nandankanan was maintained and all efforts were taken to avoid inbreeding,
he added.
Nandankanan zoo has given birth to 300 tiger cubs - 177 normal and 123
white - since 1967. However, few have survived, possibly because of
weakening genes. The zoo has so far sent out 33 normal and 22 white tigers
through exchange and direct sale programmes to different zoos in the
country except 2 normal and 6 white tigers which were sent abroad in
exchange for 25 species of other animals and birds.
The state government has fixed Rs 5 lakh as the price of an adult tiger,
deterring many zoos from procuring the animals. Patnaik admitted there was
an over population of tigers at Nandankanan and said there are plans to
give them to other zoos.
--
Héctor Paz Atencio
<glodys45@hotmail.com>
[If the zoo has sent out animals in exchange for other species, then they
may well have brought in infected animals, such as ungulates from Africa!.
Tabanids may be transferring the disease or perhaps if these animals have
died, they may have been fed to the tigers. - Mod.TG
