Date: 8 Jul 2000
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Times of India <http://www.timesofindia.com/>
<http://www.timesofindia.com/today/09hlth10.htm> 9 Jul 2000 [edited

HYDERABAD: Andhra Pradesh wildlife authorities have started screening all
the tigers in the zoos to rule out symptoms of trypanosomiasis disease
which had led to the death of 12 Royal Bengal Tigers in Nandankannan zoo in
Orissa.
"As a precautionary measure, we are taking blood samples of tigers and
testing them for trypanosomiasis virus, [parasite" the state chief
conservator of forests (Wild Life) T Ramakrishna said.
Of the total 204 tigers in the state, 183 are in the wild, while Nehru
Zoological Park here has 16 tigers and Gandhi Zoological Park in
Visakhapatnam houses 5 felines.
"All the tigers in the zoos are being vaccinated regularly and none of them
has so far shown any symptoms of the dreaded disease," he said.
The state has never in the past witnessed an outbreak of trypanosomiasis in
this virulent form, he said, adding in an isolated incident that one tiger
had died of the disease in Nehru Zoo Park in 1964.
"We are taking up prophylactic activity every year to ensure the disease
does not strike the big cats," Ramakrishna said.
--
